Communications Minister Stella Ndabeni-Abrahams has approved new requirements for South African ISPs and website owners as part of the government’s plan to fight the spread of the COVID-19 coronavirus. In a government gazette [PDF Link] dated 26 March 2020, the Department of Communications detailed interventions around the “dissemination of information” in the country. The purpose of the new directions is to facilitate the availability and use of digital technologies to combat the spread of COVID-19 in South Africa. The directions include guidelines aimed at ensuring the smooth operations of telecoms networks and disseminating COVID-19 information to citizens. The directions include a section which deals solely with the dissemination of information. The new rules include: These regulations may catch many .za website owners off guard, as many domains do not have a website hosted on the domain. ISPs may also face challenges to put measures in place to enable the removal of fake news from their platforms. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-344951 size-large" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette-640x375.jpg" alt="Gazette" width="640" height="375" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette-640x375.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette-600x351.jpg 600w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette-768x450.jpg 768w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette-1536x899.jpg 1536w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette-1200x703.jpg 1200w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Gazette.jpg 1800w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" />